br.com.summa.sol.data

Class TreeTopN<E extends Comparable<E>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • br.com.summa.sol.data.TreeTopN<E>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    TopN<E>, Serializable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>

    public class TreeTopN<E extends Comparable<E>>
extends Object
implements TopN<E>
    A generic collection limited to size N. If more than N elements are added, it will attempt to keep the greatest N elements only, discarding the others. However if there are more elements "tied" at the Nth position, they will be also kept in the collection, up to a strict limit of max elements.

    Duplicate elements are allowed. For 2 arbitrary elements x and y such that x.compareTo(y) == 0, the oldest element in this collection will be considered greater for the purpose of sorting, and perhaps also for the purpose of discarding (only when necessary to prevent more than max elements in this collection).

    This collection is optimized for large values of N, keeping its elements stored in a TreeMap of LinkedLists. For small values of N, use ListTopN instead, unless the distinction between N and max provided by TreeTopN is really needed.
    Author:
    Einar Saukas

      • TreeTopN

        public TreeTopN(int n,
        int max)
        Constructs an empty collection limited to (greatest) N elements. If there are multiple elements "tied" at the Nth position, they will be also kept in the collection, up to a strict limit of max elements. Technically, only elements strictly lower than the first N elements (when sorted in descending order) will be discarded, up to a maximum limit of max elements. Therefore this collection may get considerably larger than size N, depending on the specified limit max and the amount of "repetition" (regarding element comparison). Moreover, oldest elements in this collection will be considered greater than other "repeated" elements for the purpose of ordering, and perhaps also for the purpose of discarding (only when necessary to prevent more than max elements in this collection).

        When max = N this collection will enforce a strict limit of N (greatest) elements, discarding the others. Therefore it will work exactly like ListTopN except it will be more efficient for larger values of N.
        Parameters:
        n - intended limit N on the number of elements stored in this collection
        max - strict maximum limit on the number of elements stored in this collection

    • Method Detail

      • add

        public boolean add(E elem)
        Attempts to add the specified element to the collection. If the collection already contains (at least) N elements, and the specified new element is lower than all of them, it won't be added. Moreover, if the collection already contains max elements, and the specified new element is not greater than any of them, it won't be added either. Otherwise the specified element will be added, and other (lower) element(s) may be automatically removed in this case.
